0. Introduction¶

Video games are a medium that has taken the world by storm over the few decades they have existed. From a niche industry in the early 1980s to one that generates on the order of $100B annually, the growth has provided a brand new segment of economy to look at.

1. Data Collection¶

In order to do any analysis of data, we need data. For the purposes of this tutorial, data was retrieved from two Kaggle repositories: game data can be found here, and user data can be found here. The first repository consists of six documents, of which this tutorial will be discussing two in addition to the document from the second repository. These data are pulled from the APIs of both Steam and SteamSpy circa 2019.

This data is a mixed back of activities: "purchase" which records a user buying a game, and "play" which records the user playing it. In "purchase" rows, value is always 1, and in "play" rows, value indicates the number of hours played. Since these are separate and distinct pieces of data, we'll split them. And while we're at it, we'll get rid of the columns that are now useless.

2. Data Management¶

2a. Auxiliary Tables¶

Now that we have our data, we want it to be in a format that is easy for our code to analyze. As text isn't particularly easy to do calculations on, we can convert some of our text fields into numerical data. To do this, we will one-hot encode a few of our columns of string lists into separate tables of binary information. The tags table already follows this format and has a workable form of the steamspy_tags column, so we will let that column alone and work on the other three dimensions we want to use: genres, categories, and platforms.

In [135]:
# Convert the semicolon-separated string to a list,
# and use that to find a list of all unique genres
games['genres_list'] = games['genres'].str.split(';')
genres_set = sorted(set(sum(games['genres_list'].tolist(),[])))

# Create a new table with a column for each genre...
genres = games[['appid']]
for g in genres_set:
  genres[g] = games['genres'].apply(lambda x: 1 if g in x else 0)

2b. Narrowing the View¶

Now that we've got some key information encoded, we can drop the original text data from our source table, as well as the list versions of those columns. There is also the interesting case of the owners dimension. This would be fantastic information, if it were precise. However, these ranges are massive and not easy to work with. But that's okay! We have a count of reviews left for each game, which is almost as good. These numbers are precise, but using them comes at a cost. We have to assume that the ratio $\frac{reviews}{owners}$ is the same for all games. Obviously, this isn't going to be the case, but it's likely close, so we'll take the hit for the sake of usable data.

With all of this in mind, let's clean up games.

In [138]:
# Preserve the original

games['total_ratings'] = games['positive_ratings'] + games['negative_ratings']

# Drop columns we no longer care for

    ['platforms', 'categories', 'genres', 
     'platforms_list', 'categories_list', 'genres_list',

2c. Cleaning and Meshing¶

We're almost ready to start analysis, but our user data still isn't compatible with our game and tag information. To do this, we'll add appid to each row in our tables. Unfortunately, our name fields don't match!

In [149]:
print(games[games['name'].str.contains('Skyrim')]['name'].unique())
print(playtime[playtime['name'].str.contains('Skyrim')]['name'].unique())

['The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim' 'The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim Special Edition'
 'The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim VR']
['The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim']

Let's clean this up. We'll take out the messy bits to help the names line up.

In [150]:
def clean_name(df):
  # special characters 
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.replace('[\N{COPYRIGHT SIGN}\N{TRADE MARK SIGN}\N{REGISTERED SIGN}]', '')
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.replace(':', '')
  # the opposite of edition is subtraction
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.replace('- Game of the Year Edition', '')
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.replace(' Game of the Year Edition', '')
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.replace(' Game of the Year', '')
  # whitespace stragglers
  df['name'] = df['name'].str.strip()

clean_name(games)
clean_name(playtime)
clean_name(purchases)

print(games[games['name'].str.contains('Skyrim')]['name'].unique())
print(playtime[playtime['name'].str.contains('Skyrim')]['name'].unique())

['The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim' 'The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim Special Edition'
 'The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim VR']
['The Elder Scrolls V Skyrim']

Now we have a match. Catching every edge case is a bit tedious to do manually, so we'll merge what we've got left and make sure we still have a decent amount of data to work with.

3. Data Exploration and Analysis¶

One of the most immediate questions we can answer is: what are the most popular games? We can take purchase and playtime data and look at the top games to see what people are buying and playing, and if there are any discrepancies.

In [255]:
n_games = 10
# grab the top 10 games by purchase count
agg_purchases = purchases.groupby('name')['name'].count().sort_values(ascending=False)
agg_purchases = pd.DataFrame(
    {'name': agg_purchases.index, 
     'times_purchased': agg_purchases.values})
agg_p = agg_purchases[0:n_games]
# top 10 games by playtime
agg_hours = playtime.groupby('name')['value'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
agg_hours = pd.DataFrame(
    {'name': agg_hours.index, 
     'total_playtime': agg_hours.values / 1000})
agg_h = agg_hours[0:n_games]
# graph 'em
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12,n_games))
sb.barplot(data=agg_p, y='name', x='times_purchased', ax=ax[0])
ax[0].set(xlabel='Total Purchases', ylabel='Game')
sb.barplot(data=agg_h, y='name', x='total_playtime', ax=ax[1])
ax[1].set(xlabel='Total Playtime (x1000 Hours)', ylabel='Game')
ax[1].yaxis.tick_right()
ax[1].yaxis.set_label_position('right')

Dota 2 seems to reign supreme in both of these categories! However, there's a lot different about these two visuals in order and content. Could the games in either category have something in common? Let's take a look at the most common tags in the games in each set.

It looks like free-to-play games are the culprit here! 5 of the most owned games are free, which makes sense intuitively. Anyone can "purchase" the game and never play it, so we should expect to see this difference. According to tags, multiplayer/co-op games dominate both charts. The free-to-play tag places 4th among game ownership, but drops out of the top ten entirely for playtime. Rising to replace it are tags such as "moddable" and "character customization," perhaps showing that when given the opportunity to tailor the play experience, users tend to spend more time with the game.

Like any art form, video games develop trends. These trends can be seen in the tendencies of consumers as well as those of creators. For this section, we will be comparing trends across the genres with the most published games. First, we have to figure out what those genres are.

In [11]:
# count total games across each genre, take top 5 ignoring 'appid'
top_genres = genres.sum().sort_values(ascending=False)[1:11].keys()
top_genres = top_genres.to_list()
top_genres

# create a list of ids for each genre
genre_ids = []
for g in top_genres:
  genre_ids.append(genres[genres[g] == 1]['appid'])

# create new sub-frames for each genre
genre_games = []
for i in genre_ids:
  genre_games.append(games[games['appid'].isin(i.array)])

The clear outlier here is the "Indie" genre, which says more about how the game is made than the game's actual content. All of the top genres have been ballooning massively since approximately 2014. They all experience troughs at around the same time, meaning those dips are less indicative of a genre-specific shortcoming and more related to the industry as a whole.

However, this only tells part of the story.

As we can see with the discrepancy between ownership and playtime, just because games are being bought does not mean they're being played. With thousands of games being published each year and only a few making headlines, it makes sense that many games slip through the cracks. To evaluate what's not being played, we can look at the lowest average playtimes of games - that is, the fewest hours played per owner.

Another piece of information we can utilize to gauge the quality of a game is the user ratings. We can pull that information back in from our games table, do a quick calculation, and graph it against the average playtime.

This graph tells an entirely different story from the previous one. Indie games, while being the most prolific genre in terms of game publication, generate much less revenue than action and adventure titles. Casual games, the third most popular genre, generate the least of the top five, with very little growth overall. Casual games appear not to have many players, despite being a popular genre for creators.

This metric isn't perfect, however. The entire free-to-play genre has no revenue of sales, but may have other transactions not accounted for in this data set.
